raw_data.title: Jr. BI Developer
raw_data.description: The Jr. BI Developer is responsible for building, implementing, and supporting BI solutions.  The Jr. BI Developer will work in all stages of BI project work (requirements and logical design, physical design, implementation, testing and deployment).  The Jr. BI Developer utilizes BI implementation methodologies to collect data from multiple disparate sources and consolidates into data marts and data warehouses, as well as enables users across the organization to complete self-service reporting and analytics by developing the necessary solutions.  The BI Developer also communicates with the appropriate teams to ensure that assignments are delivered with the highest of quality and in accordance to standards.  Responsibilities include translating business needs to technical specifications; dashboards, alerts; creating tools to store data (e.g., OLAP cubes); maintaining and supporting data analytics platforms; evaluating and improving existing BI systems; collaborating with teams to integrate systems; developing and executing database queries and conduct analyses; and developing and updating technical documentation.

raw_data.title: Senior ETL Developer/Architect
raw_data.description: The Senior ETL Developer/Architect will be responsible for driving the overall design and determining the ETL architecture necessary for the delivery team to develop and implement large complex migration programs.  This position will consult with development teams and work closely with vendor partner, developers, data architects, project management, business analysts, and other areas to deliver in line with our strategy, capabilities, and processes.  Implement large-scale data ecosystems including data management, governance, and the integration of structured and unstructured data to generate insights leveraging various platforms.  Leverage automation, cognitive, and science-based techniques to manage data, predict scenarios, and prescribe actions.  Drive operational efficiency by maintaining data ecosystems, sourcing analytics expertise, and providing offerings for continuous insights and improvements.  Design, develop, and support a reference architecture to move data from varying data platforms into the data warehouse solution.  This includes implementing a structure to:  determine traceability and lineage of data through the process, accounting for quantitative and qualitative changes, data leakage, etc.; design and implement standards to modularize the process using high cohesion and low coupling to allow easy restarts anywhere along the process; create a structure to make visible the flow of data and time of packages so the nightly process schedule can be easily understood and modified, along with alerting processes when tolerance boundaries are exceeded; and develop an optimized architecture for job scheduling for data warehouse batch processes.  Perform ETL design, data architecture, data management and data analysis.  Manage the technical delivery of medium to large, complex projects on-time, on-budget, and with targeted zero defects.  Provide planning, estimation, scheduling, prioritization, and coordination of technical activities related to system development.  Ensure system alignment to Enterprise Architecture policies and best practices; ensure that process methodologies are followed in system development.  Manage day-to-day technical challenges and communicate to project manager any risks or issues associated with development.  Identify opportunities for system reuse and system simplification.

raw_data.title: Senior Application Architect
raw_data.description: This position is responsible for designing and implementing information systems and solutions which address the enterprise infrastructure and application needs of the organization and clients, leading the application development team and supervise the design, testing, and modification phases of multiple initiatives.  The ability to think strategically and position products for long-term success must be demonstrated.  The Senior Application Architect will document and present design artifacts to the internal team and clients throughout the project lifecycle, ensure systems operate securely and that applications are working at optimal levels, investigate and recommend new technologies, and investigate and develop POCs to prove concepts, reliability, and functionality.  Additional tasks include independent work and managing multiple concurrent initiatives, the ability to lead multiple teams and advise on development or architecture solutions as needed, the ability to participate and develop ASP.Net code, Angular, as well as any supporting systems to ensure applications meet or exceed client requirements while demonstrating application prototypes and integrating user feedback.  This positions will analyze system requirements and prioritize tasks, collaborate with Sr Management, business sponsors, and stakeholders on application needs and requirements, write clean, testable code using the ASP.NET programming language, develop technical specifications and architecture, test and debug various .NET applications, review and refactor code, deploy fully functional applications, upgrade existing programs, support Junior Developers’ work, document development and operational procedures, Train and mentor others and provide consulting, troubleshooting, and technical support services to clients.

raw_data.title: Data Architect

Ensures data lineage is consistent across applications and data sources while also developing and communicating strategies and common approaches for data acquisition, data access, and data archiving.  Creates standards for how data will be stored, consumed, integrated, and managed by different data entities and technology systems.  Selects frameworks, develops and communicates common approaches, and develops roadmaps that enable the implementation of intended business architecture.  Creates diagrams showing key data entities, and creates an inventory of the data needed to implement the architecture vision.  Creates and reviews data designs to ensure that conceptual, logical, and physical data models are consistent with architecture.  Ensures that data flow is consistent, traceable, and meets organizational needs.  Serve as a data entrepreneur, leading the transformation of historical data structures and business data, extract meaning out of data, and create an enterprise data model.  Assists in creating an enterprise architecture approach for solving short-term and long-term strategic initiatives.  This position works closely with clients and end-users to examine existing processes and develop solutions.  Works with Business users and Business Analysts to gather requirements in different forms including:  interviews, facilitated sessions, and reviewing current-state documented data structures and processes.  Acts as technical lead to assess client’s current state environment and offer estimates, works with project manager to create detailed project plans, and provides leadership and guidance to the data warehouse technical team.  Provides data analysis expertise.  Ensures common application architectural framework across different subject areas and conformance with best practices.  Consults with key individuals across multiple projects regarding the usage and application of Business Intelligence and Data Warehousing architectural standards.  Provides input and architectural guidance for ETL architecture and processes.  Implements data quality and data governance processes.  Evaluates, recommends, and implements Business Intelligence Tools to meet technical and business requirements.

raw_data.title: Data Warehouse Architect
raw_data.description: Data Warehouse Architects develop applications that store, retrieve, and secure data.  They communicate with the people who will be using and managing the application to determine what features are needed to help them work more efficiently and effectively, then plan and design the application, eventually installing and testing it to ensure it meets its users' needs.  These Architects work as a member of a team with users, managers, administrators, and other database architects to conduct needs assessments, review database designs with important stakeholders, plan and implement security processes, and train team members.

raw_data.title: BI Architect
raw_data.description: BI architects work with clients to develop data structures that help them drive their business and marketing strategies.  The data is also used by the organization for identifying market trends.  The BI Architect designs, develops, implements, and oversees data structures, data warehousing, and repositories, as well as report preparation.  They work extensively with software focused on market trends both historical and current to help create strategies for the organization.  The BI architect works with legacy software and extracts data from it and loads the data into currently used software.  They work closely with other information technology specialists within the client organization to ensure the optimization of existing data structures ensuring that both legacy data and current are seamlessly integrated into the organization's larger information technology network such that the data are readily available for decisions that drive the organization's business vision.  Business intelligence architects serve as data collectors from a number of sources ranging from past and current market trends to industry reports. They will often analyze competitive market strategies by studying similar products from other organizations and reporting the results of the analysis to the top executives.

raw_data.title: Enterprise Architect
raw_data.description: Enterprise Architects meet with executives or clients to understand the company's business strategy and processes, so these can be translated into the information technology structure.  Through research, they utilize the technology and data capturing standards seen in similar businesses, making partnerships between organizations easier.  The architecture typically includes the necessary applications and programs, and is a dynamic technical system that can grow with the company.  An Enterprise Architect will locate gaps or problem areas with the current technology, suggest software and hardware updates, developing a data model for tracking and finding patterns in data collected through business practices, and provide mentoring and knowledge transfer for new users.

raw_data.title: MDM/DQM Enterprise Architect
raw_data.description: The Enterprise Architect/Master Data Management (MDM)/Data Quality Management (DQM) Architect is responsible for Senior-level Architectural leadership, providing trusted advice and direction to help Client achieve its strategic business and technical goals and objectives.  Provide state of the art architectural direction, best practices, and deep experience in Enterprise Architecture and Master Data Management (MDM) – bringing Industry-leading and proven architectural-level knowledge, disciplines and skillsets to develop Enterprise-level architectural designs, serving as the blueprints and vision for enterprise data foundations, including Master Data and MDM capabilities, Operational Data Stores, Data Lakes, Enterprise Data Warehouses (EDWs), Data Hubs, Data Marts, etc.).  Development of architectural-level artifacts in the creation of the Client’s End State Enterprise Architecture Vision, with a focus on the ecosystems and their design and management of strategic foundational enterprise data resources.

raw_data.title: Data Modeler
raw_data.description: As they work to design and build useful databases, Data Modelers do a variety of different tasks.  They must identify business needs by identifying areas where data can be used to improve business activities, and defining business users’ requirements.  Then, using their understanding of data flows, they propose and implement innovative data solutions.  They create and maintain Data Models and work closely with the Database Architects to create optimal physical data models of datasets, then create and maintain data maps and systems interrelationship diagrams for data domains and systems.  They define and govern data modeling and design standards, tools, best practices, and related development methodologies for the client.  They also set standards for document naming, security, and lifecycle & retention architecture.  Based off of their data an analysis, Data Modelers make recommendations for standardization and proper data usage.  They champion the usage of data in business, and communicate the benefits and return on investment for application and product owners.

raw_data.title: Data Governance Consultant
raw_data.description: A Data Governance Consultant is responsible for activities around Data Governance, assessments, strategies, data quality management and mentoring clients on how to implement DG programs.  This position works closely with clients to create or enhance DG programs and to help clients mature their DG capabilities.  The DG lead consultant will help lead clients in the process of implementing these reusable deliverables and processes for clients.  The following is the framework, templates and tools that will be implemented from customer to customer:  implementation framework and roadmap applying Industry best practices and reusable deliverable templates to help accelerate Data Governance Program Implementation efforts and reduce costs, Overview Presentations - education to Executive level sponsors and Core Data Governance Team, Data Governance Charter (A foundational document with Data Governance mission, vision, policies, and standards, Enterprise information management guidelines, objectives, roles & responsibilities), program Backlog (data-related Issues, needs and opportunities collected from the client and organized into themes such as Data Quality, Data Acquisition, Data Standardization, Data Security, Big Data, etc.), initial scope for the Data Governance Program and Pilot Project (e.g., selection of 1 or 2 quick win ideas to implement – a way to pilot the act of governing by the business over their data and piloting of the related data governance processes), communication/change management plan, organization structure (decision making authority) defined/confirmed (executive and work group levels), work group formed to include business and I/T leaders and subject matter experts, overview of the traditional roles and responsibilities of being a Data Steward provided to the group, meeting structure and agenda template and meetings following the standard agenda, Issue Intake Triage Worksheet, Home Page template, initial toolset strategy, initial business glossary (standard definitions for key concepts and terms), pilot project under (consulting/mentoring), self-sufficient in running meetings, and pilot lessons learned.

raw_data.title: Predictive/Data Scientist
raw_data.description: The Predictive/Data Scientist is tasked with solving our most complex quantitative, statistical, and data-oriented problems.  Use a powerful blend of business acumen, analytics, mathematics, programming, and modeling to provide strategic recommendations, insights, and products across a diverse set of business areas and industries.  Functional projects typically include deep-dive operational analyses, data wrangling and processing, programmatic automation, and predictive modeling.  Our data scientist operates both independently and collaboratively with wide-latitude, moving in and out of dynamic teams and are often asked to tackle complicated questions that require creative solutions.  Conduct advanced analyses and statistical deep-dives, with a focus on producing actionable recommendations and strategic guidance for decision makers.  Develop and deploy custom models and algorithms using Python, R, and machine learning platforms.  Mine, clean, process, transform and join data from a variety of sources.  Identify, wrangle, scrape, and assemble new data sources from the web, data aggregators, and public sources.  Build rich, interactive reports, dashboards, and visualizations.  Compile and present key findings and reports to key stakeholders, including senior leadership.  Continuously seek out opportunities to add value through programmatic solutions to manual tasks.  Be a subject matter expert within the data science field.  Continuously learn, grow, and explore new emerging technologies.  Be an exceptional problem solver, source of creative solutions, and take the initiative to share new ideas, methodologies, and strategies.

raw_data.title: Project Manager
raw_data.description: Project Managers are responsible for planning, directing, and coordinating project management activities of designated project(s), ensuring that the goals and objectives of the project(s) are accomplished within the prescribed time frame and requirements.  Must have excellent relationship building, leadership, and client management skills.  Must have a deep understanding of project management tools and approaches to managing complex projects.  The Project Manager will provide leadership and management of standard project practices following an established Project Management Methodology (PMM) and System Development Methodology (SDM).  Project Managers lead the process to complete project charter and obtain necessary approvals, determine resources required to accomplish project objectives, conduct or participate in stakeholder meetings, and contribute to the overall team effort as needed to accomplish successful project results.  They create and publish project documents to include project scope, work breakdown structure, risk assessment and response, critical path, time estimates, schedules, and budget projections, as well as create and execute plans for communication, change control, quality control, and specific coordination of activities.  PMs work with Business users to gather requirements in different forms, including facilitated interview sessions.  The Project Manager will oversee execution of project tasks, monitoring performance, creation of burn down charts and solving project slippage and/or constraints in a timely manner, manage stakeholder expectations by utilizing risk mitigation and problem solving, control project scope and changes, schedule, budget, and status reporting.  They also facilitate closeout activities, retrospectives/lessons learned, and customer feedback.
